...and then tomorrow you focus on the next day. If you fall short, start over. If you have to go back to square one half way though, that's fine. Despite what people might tell you, there IS value in just making the effort.

So, if you're not making a new year's resolution, why not? I know you've got something you want, something you wish you could do. Fucking do it! If your first thought is how you won't make it, push that out of your head. Don't think about down the road. Focus on tomorrow...

creep into my life and take over. Over the last few days I've had the epiphany that most of the shit I stress about is other people's problems! I lay awake at night wondering how OTHER people are going to make it. And I'm done with that. No more.

...but helping is not doing the caring for you. From now on, my cheer leading has a short shelf life. If I'm helping you to be better and feel your effort slack, I'm done. This all sounds harsh, but I've come to realize I've let WAY too much of this bullshit slowly...

I've come to realize this year that there are WAY too many people in my life that have just given up. I normally figure this out when I realize I'm starting to shoulder the mental and sometimes physical burden of keeping them going. I love to help...

...on them right off the bat. Encourage them to succeed! Even if they do fall short, at least they're TRYING! At least they have some inkling of desire to be better that extends beyond wishful thinking. That's admirable.

That's your business. But don't think that gives you any kind of high ground. And if you respond to someone's resolution with some kind of bet that they won't see it through...again...fuck the fucking fuck off, you fucking fuck. They sure don't need you coming down...

Don't don't be a downer on people trying to move forward and better themselves just because you've given up and decided to find contentment in stagnation. I have zero time for that shit. If you want to coast through life, not doing a damn thing different day to day...

And while we're on the subject of resolutions: if you're one of those people who likes to roll their eyes at people who make them, or who gets some kind of smug superiority about the fact that you're not making any...fuck off. Seriously, fuck right the hell off.

Just, everyone please know that this is the kind of shit you put trans people through when you don't respect pronouns and names. It's not a small thing. It's not benign details. It seriously crushes a person's world.
I have hundreds of people in my life that know me for me, but they're not there with me in these moments. They can't be there to help keep me grounded in reality.

I'm tweeting all of this because I know it's coming and I'm trying to strengthen my resolve. Deadnames and misgenders hurt. They rob you of confidence, distort how you see your reflection. They make you question everything you say and do, wondering if it's too masculine.

How do you reconcile looking at me and then using a male pronoun? I know I sound like I'm bragging, but screw it. I've worked hard in my transition. I put a lot of effort into this body. When a family member calls me "he" all I can wonder is, how do you still see that?

That's what makes it so jarring. I pass for cis female everywhere I go. I haven't been called sir by a stranger in almost a year! I know memories play a big role, but Jesus Christ...LOOK AT ME! I've done modeling for God sake (charity event)! Straight men hit on me. I'm no man!
I need to add, for the record, that I go to these things in no way LOOKING like a man. I wear my normal clothes and put on some subtle makeup. I look 100% female, or at least I feel like I do.

Seeing family today. It's the only environment left in my life where people see me as a man. With each visit I try to ready myself for it, but the experience is always a shock to the system. Nowhere else do I hear my old name or male pronouns.
@OhMiaGod I go see my parents today. It will be another holiday of begrudging toleration of my presence sprinkled with a few dead names and wrong pronouns.   Merry Christmas.
